WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:04.760 --> 00:00:08.820
MOONLIT BESHIMOV: Show of hands,
who wants to make more money?

00:00:08.820 --> 00:00:09.840
Me, too.

00:00:09.840 --> 00:00:11.160
Thank you.

00:00:11.160 --> 00:00:13.380
What do you think
your financial advisor

00:00:13.380 --> 00:00:18.870
would say if you ask him
this question and how?

00:00:18.870 --> 00:00:22.260
Nobel Prize winning
economist Harry Markowitz

00:00:22.260 --> 00:00:25.320
once said that he would
never be 100% invested

00:00:25.320 --> 00:00:29.040
in stocks or bonds or cash.

00:00:29.040 --> 00:00:32.369
If you think about it,
games are not so different.

00:00:32.369 --> 00:00:34.970
Would you bet your
entire revenue stream

00:00:34.970 --> 00:00:38.260
on one source of income?

00:00:38.260 --> 00:00:43.260
A more sustainable revenue
model calls for a mindset shift.

00:00:43.260 --> 00:00:45.000
Our industry seems
to operate in the way

00:00:45.000 --> 00:00:49.500
that your monetization model
is determined by your genre.

00:00:49.500 --> 00:00:52.620
Ads for hyper casual,
IAP for rest of mobile,

00:00:52.620 --> 00:00:55.620
and subscriptions
for PC and console.

00:00:55.620 --> 00:00:57.700
This has worked so far.

00:00:57.700 --> 00:01:00.510
But in this talk, I'd
like to invite all of you

00:01:00.510 --> 00:01:04.900
to challenge these
assumptions together with me.

00:01:04.900 --> 00:01:07.870
Our economists friend Harry
said that we shouldn't put all

00:01:07.870 --> 00:01:10.420
of our eggs in the same basket.

00:01:10.420 --> 00:01:13.180
Can we take learning
from other genre

00:01:13.180 --> 00:01:15.700
and rethink our
current strategy?

00:01:15.700 --> 00:01:18.370
No rule saying that you
have to do something

00:01:18.370 --> 00:01:22.860
just because you're
born this way, right?

00:01:22.860 --> 00:01:25.950
In 15 minutes, you'll hear
from one of your peers' about

00:01:25.950 --> 00:01:27.360
their innovation.

00:01:27.360 --> 00:01:30.030
But first, let me set
the stage and talk

00:01:30.030 --> 00:01:33.700
about monetization
diversification, the why,

00:01:33.700 --> 00:01:36.590
the what, and the how.

00:01:36.590 --> 00:01:39.110
Why diversify?

00:01:39.110 --> 00:01:41.020
Our economist friend
Harry said that we

00:01:41.020 --> 00:01:44.890
should balance our income
sources because it decreases

00:01:44.890 --> 00:01:47.690
risk and increases revenue.

00:01:47.690 --> 00:01:49.410
True or not true?

00:01:49.410 --> 00:01:52.600
If you disagree, come
find me after this talk.

00:01:52.600 --> 00:01:56.030
What you may not know is
that we also have big data

00:01:56.030 --> 00:01:57.980
to back up this claim.

00:01:57.980 --> 00:02:00.380
We plotted the top grossing
games on this graph

00:02:00.380 --> 00:02:01.550
to your right.

00:02:01.550 --> 00:02:03.500
Each dot is a game.

00:02:03.500 --> 00:02:07.700
On the x-axis is the percentage
of the game's revenue driven

00:02:07.700 --> 00:02:10.910
by its top 5% of buyers.

00:02:10.910 --> 00:02:16.290
On the y-axis is the game's
turn buyer's reactivation rate.

00:02:16.290 --> 00:02:19.780
This means that the more to the
right, the more concentrated

00:02:19.780 --> 00:02:22.040
is your game's revenue.

00:02:22.040 --> 00:02:25.940
This negative correlation
shows that if a game squeezes

00:02:25.940 --> 00:02:29.570
its buyers, then they're
also less likely to come back

00:02:29.570 --> 00:02:32.400
if they ever leave.

00:02:32.400 --> 00:02:37.440
Therefore, we call this
philosophy $1 out of everyone

00:02:37.440 --> 00:02:43.690
is more sustainable than
$100 out of one player.

00:02:43.690 --> 00:02:47.610
Now, if I got you thinking about
the diversification, let's talk

00:02:47.610 --> 00:02:51.210
about some of the
trends we've observed.

00:02:51.210 --> 00:02:54.480
Subscriptions,
rewarded ads, and IAP--

00:02:54.480 --> 00:02:58.910
raise your hand if you have at
least one of these implemented.

00:02:58.910 --> 00:03:01.400
What about two of these?

00:03:01.400 --> 00:03:03.160
All three?

00:03:03.160 --> 00:03:04.740
Good for you.

00:03:04.740 --> 00:03:06.190
So here's the deal.

00:03:06.190 --> 00:03:07.660
I would not claim
that everything

00:03:07.660 --> 00:03:10.660
I'll be sharing with you
today will be groundbreaking.

00:03:10.660 --> 00:03:13.180
But my hope for you is
that, after this talk,

00:03:13.180 --> 00:03:17.000
you will have learned something
new and, more importantly,

00:03:17.000 --> 00:03:19.720
find the inspiration
from your peers' stories

00:03:19.720 --> 00:03:24.870
to try something new and add
to your current strategy.

00:03:24.870 --> 00:03:28.590
Now, raise your hand if you have
subscriptions in your games.

00:03:28.590 --> 00:03:29.852
Are you thinking about it?

00:03:29.852 --> 00:03:31.560
Raise your hand if
you thinking about it.

00:03:31.560 --> 00:03:33.210
Awesome.

00:03:33.210 --> 00:03:36.510
Subscriptions is not a
foreign concept in gaming.

00:03:36.510 --> 00:03:40.200
From PC to console, many
have use subscriptions

00:03:40.200 --> 00:03:42.340
as a content path.

00:03:42.340 --> 00:03:44.580
However, today I
would like to talk

00:03:44.580 --> 00:03:47.490
to you about a different
kind of subscription.

00:03:47.490 --> 00:03:49.950
Instead of bundles,
how are mobile games

00:03:49.950 --> 00:03:52.680
layering subscriptions
on top of IAP

00:03:52.680 --> 00:03:55.620
to create different tiers
of premium experiences?

00:03:58.210 --> 00:04:01.120
The momentum around
subscription has accelerated

00:04:01.120 --> 00:04:03.050
in mobile in recent years.

00:04:03.050 --> 00:04:06.280
On Play, we've seen a global
mobile gaming subscriptions

00:04:06.280 --> 00:04:10.760
growth at 70% year over year.

00:04:10.760 --> 00:04:13.540
In fact, those who
implement subscriptions

00:04:13.540 --> 00:04:17.660
reported a boost in both
retention and revenue.

00:04:17.660 --> 00:04:20.140
[INAUDIBLE] saw 20% more play.

00:04:20.140 --> 00:04:25.120
And Scopely reported higher LTV
when they have subscriptions.

00:04:25.120 --> 00:04:27.215
If those are not
enough reasons for you,

00:04:27.215 --> 00:04:29.110
at Google I/O earlier
this year and also

00:04:29.110 --> 00:04:32.800
this morning, we talk
about digital wellbeing.

00:04:32.800 --> 00:04:35.920
Many top developers like
IBM are prioritizing

00:04:35.920 --> 00:04:38.320
sustainable growth.

00:04:38.320 --> 00:04:42.220
So I challenge you, leaders
in the mobile game industry,

00:04:42.220 --> 00:04:44.500
to think about what
does digital wellbeing

00:04:44.500 --> 00:04:47.290
look like as a mobile game.

00:04:47.290 --> 00:04:50.860
With subscriptions, can we
restructure short term impulse

00:04:50.860 --> 00:04:54.880
buys into a long term
sustainable benefits?

00:04:54.880 --> 00:04:57.430
Maybe instead of eating all
of your Halloween candies

00:04:57.430 --> 00:05:01.590
in one go and possibly
regret it next morning,

00:05:01.590 --> 00:05:05.410
can't we instead have
something sweet every day

00:05:05.410 --> 00:05:06.630
for the next few months?

00:05:09.260 --> 00:05:14.140
Designing subscriptions requires
a mindset shift from IAP.

00:05:14.140 --> 00:05:17.600
You may be tempted to repackage
IAP SKUs into subscription

00:05:17.600 --> 00:05:18.920
bundles.

00:05:18.920 --> 00:05:20.070
It works.

00:05:20.070 --> 00:05:22.460
But there's so much
more you can do.

00:05:22.460 --> 00:05:24.800
The keyword here is access.

00:05:24.800 --> 00:05:27.560
The main difference between
IAP and subscription

00:05:27.560 --> 00:05:30.950
is that, while IAP is about
ownership where the users get

00:05:30.950 --> 00:05:33.650
to keep what they
buy, subscription's

00:05:33.650 --> 00:05:36.440
about access, access
of different tiers

00:05:36.440 --> 00:05:38.540
or premium
experiences and access

00:05:38.540 --> 00:05:42.770
that you can gain and lose.

00:05:42.770 --> 00:05:45.620
There are two new use
cases of subscriptions.

00:05:45.620 --> 00:05:49.220
The first is aimed at
converting your buyers.

00:05:49.220 --> 00:05:53.380
These buyers are often motivated
by a good financial deal.

00:05:53.380 --> 00:05:56.600
Scopely subscriptions
offer exclusive rewards

00:05:56.600 --> 00:06:01.380
that a early buyer would
want on top of IAP deal.

00:06:01.380 --> 00:06:06.510
[INAUDIBLE] with loss protection
and higher daily caps.

00:06:06.510 --> 00:06:09.840
This observation aims to
increase these early buyer's

00:06:09.840 --> 00:06:13.710
time spending game to form
a habit of playing still

00:06:13.710 --> 00:06:17.390
early in their lifecycle.

00:06:17.390 --> 00:06:20.090
The second use case of
in-game subscriptions

00:06:20.090 --> 00:06:24.170
is to create a loyalty program
for your high value buyers.

00:06:24.170 --> 00:06:27.380
Much like the mileage
program by airlines,

00:06:27.380 --> 00:06:30.770
these players are often
motivated by prestige,

00:06:30.770 --> 00:06:33.430
rewards for the commitment
in your game, or just

00:06:33.430 --> 00:06:36.920
to live a more
premium experience.

00:06:36.920 --> 00:06:39.320
Ludia offers their
VIP subscribers

00:06:39.320 --> 00:06:42.740
extra currency,
exclusive tournaments,

00:06:42.740 --> 00:06:45.650
early access to new
content, and access--

00:06:45.650 --> 00:06:47.420
again, the key word is access--

00:06:47.420 --> 00:06:52.850
to a special durable that may
even strengthen with time.

00:06:52.850 --> 00:06:56.450
Designing access is key to
meet your in-game subscription

00:06:56.450 --> 00:07:00.260
additive to your
existing IAP economy.

00:07:00.260 --> 00:07:03.500
If you're thinking, OK,
what about cannibalization?

00:07:03.500 --> 00:07:05.360
Hold that thought,
and wait for Fay.

00:07:08.070 --> 00:07:10.200
Now, raise your hand
if you have rewarded

00:07:10.200 --> 00:07:12.840
ads implemented in your games.

00:07:12.840 --> 00:07:13.500
Awesome.

00:07:13.500 --> 00:07:17.068
Those with your hands raised,
you can take a nap now.

00:07:17.068 --> 00:07:19.110
Although you may want to
stay awake for something

00:07:19.110 --> 00:07:22.380
that may be a surprise to you.

00:07:22.380 --> 00:07:26.130
Earlier this year, the Google
AdMob conducted the research

00:07:26.130 --> 00:07:29.430
and uncovered a growing
segment of developers,

00:07:29.430 --> 00:07:32.280
who were previously
IAP only, are now

00:07:32.280 --> 00:07:35.380
rethinking their overall
monetization strategy

00:07:35.380 --> 00:07:39.723
and, as a result, are
implementing rewarded ads.

00:07:39.723 --> 00:07:41.640
There are three main
reasons of why you should

00:07:41.640 --> 00:07:43.860
think about rewarded ads.

00:07:43.860 --> 00:07:47.850
The first, [INAUDIBLE] will
entice non-payers, especially

00:07:47.850 --> 00:07:51.600
in developing countries,
emerging markets.

00:07:51.600 --> 00:07:54.300
These players, while they might
be more reluctant to take out

00:07:54.300 --> 00:07:56.910
their wallet and
make purchases, they

00:07:56.910 --> 00:08:00.270
might be more willing to
trade with their time instead.

00:08:00.270 --> 00:08:02.400
The second benefit
is that it also

00:08:02.400 --> 00:08:07.450
increases overall engagement
across buyers and non-buyers.

00:08:07.450 --> 00:08:09.930
Many game developers
use rewarded ads

00:08:09.930 --> 00:08:16.020
as a way to extend gameplay or
gift a minimal amount of IAP.

00:08:16.020 --> 00:08:19.330
This increases time
spent for everyone,

00:08:19.330 --> 00:08:22.350
which, in turn, increases
social liquidity, which

00:08:22.350 --> 00:08:27.410
then enhances the experience
of everybody playing.

00:08:27.410 --> 00:08:31.670
Now, the third reason, which
may be a surprise to you,

00:08:31.670 --> 00:08:36.530
is that it also
predicts IAP conversion.

00:08:36.530 --> 00:08:39.500
Kongregate found that,
across six of their games,

00:08:39.500 --> 00:08:43.190
players who watched an ad
in their very first session

00:08:43.190 --> 00:08:48.800
are 2.5 to 5 times more likely
to make subsequent purchases.

00:08:48.800 --> 00:08:50.660
Of course, we can't
say that watching an ad

00:08:50.660 --> 00:08:52.670
will cause you to spend.

00:08:52.670 --> 00:08:56.840
But there is a clear correlation
between the group of people

00:08:56.840 --> 00:09:00.350
who watch ads and the group of
people who are likely to make

00:09:00.350 --> 00:09:01.370
in-app purchases.

00:09:04.270 --> 00:09:06.810
Now, AdMob also shared
with us a framework

00:09:06.810 --> 00:09:10.020
to help you optimize
your rewarded ads design.

00:09:10.020 --> 00:09:12.560
Let's see what Kongregate
has to say for each of these.

00:09:15.710 --> 00:09:19.670
For placement, rewarded ads
should be core to your gameplay

00:09:19.670 --> 00:09:22.070
as part of the in-game economy.

00:09:22.070 --> 00:09:25.610
The reward itself should
be useful, meaningful,

00:09:25.610 --> 00:09:27.540
while not competing
directly with IAP.

00:09:30.100 --> 00:09:34.100
For targeting, everybody should
have access to rewarded ads.

00:09:34.100 --> 00:09:37.160
But the user should
initiate the experience

00:09:37.160 --> 00:09:41.330
as to ensure to not
interrupt their gameplay.

00:09:41.330 --> 00:09:44.960
For cadence, more isn't
necessarily better.

00:09:44.960 --> 00:09:48.200
Kongregate found that six to
eight ads views per viewer

00:09:48.200 --> 00:09:51.440
per day maximizes
return with the option

00:09:51.440 --> 00:09:55.560
to watch at least
one per sessions.

00:09:55.560 --> 00:09:58.620
For measurement, remember
to segment your core health

00:09:58.620 --> 00:10:02.060
metrics by app
viewership and frequency.

00:10:02.060 --> 00:10:04.440
And if you notice a
certain cohort of users

00:10:04.440 --> 00:10:08.190
are spending less time or
money, test and iterate.

00:10:08.190 --> 00:10:10.410
Use this framework.

00:10:10.410 --> 00:10:13.980
Now, if you're itching to
test out rewarded ads quickly,

00:10:13.980 --> 00:10:16.290
this morning we announced
rewarded products

00:10:16.290 --> 00:10:18.090
that's coming soon.

00:10:18.090 --> 00:10:23.580
Directly in your console, this
uses the same API calls as IAP.

00:10:23.580 --> 00:10:25.980
If you're interested, talk
to your Play BD manager.

00:10:28.800 --> 00:10:32.820
Lastly, IAP-- I will not ask for
hands as I assume most of you

00:10:32.820 --> 00:10:34.950
have IAP implemented.

00:10:34.950 --> 00:10:38.790
But for now, [INAUDIBLE]
why game developer who found

00:10:38.790 --> 00:10:42.700
success previously with ads
are now also pushing for IAP.

00:10:45.830 --> 00:10:48.500
Similar to the trend
with rewarded ads--

00:10:48.500 --> 00:10:51.410
while IAP itself
isn't new, what is new

00:10:51.410 --> 00:10:54.650
is the growing number of
developers, who were previously

00:10:54.650 --> 00:10:59.120
ads only, are now adding
IAP to their existing titles

00:10:59.120 --> 00:11:01.670
or developing new
IAP based titles

00:11:01.670 --> 00:11:06.080
to increase their
portfolio diversity.

00:11:06.080 --> 00:11:10.070
For example, Tapps games,
a Brazilian developer,

00:11:10.070 --> 00:11:12.470
is known for their
hyper casual games

00:11:12.470 --> 00:11:16.640
but decided to focus on IAP
in their Bid Wars titles.

00:11:16.640 --> 00:11:20.300
After growing the IAP
revenue by 200% and more,

00:11:20.300 --> 00:11:25.280
IAP is now an integral
part of the strategy.

00:11:25.280 --> 00:11:28.510
Let's remind ourselves
the advantages of IAP.

00:11:28.510 --> 00:11:31.540
First, it can be run and
developed by a simple team,

00:11:31.540 --> 00:11:34.310
by a nimble team with
simple infrastructure.

00:11:34.310 --> 00:11:36.580
We've seen teams as
small as 10 people

00:11:36.580 --> 00:11:39.300
managing multi-million
dollar titles.

00:11:39.300 --> 00:11:42.550
Second, instead
relying on a huge user

00:11:42.550 --> 00:11:45.570
base or massive
installs, IAP pushes

00:11:45.570 --> 00:11:49.930
us to think about long term,
sustainable business metrics.

00:11:49.930 --> 00:11:53.290
And last, IAP gives you
control and flexibility

00:11:53.290 --> 00:11:54.820
over your game and your revenue.

00:11:58.050 --> 00:12:00.450
Now, for those of you who
are thinking about IAP,

00:12:00.450 --> 00:12:04.210
let's quickly touch on
the design framework.

00:12:04.210 --> 00:12:08.460
Yodo1 is the Chinese
publisher of Rodeo Stampede.

00:12:08.460 --> 00:12:12.690
They managed to shift their
ads to IAP ratio from 30% IAP

00:12:12.690 --> 00:12:14.860
to 60% IAP.

00:12:14.860 --> 00:12:17.290
Let's see what they recommend.

00:12:17.290 --> 00:12:20.890
For design, keep it
simple and flexible.

00:12:20.890 --> 00:12:24.220
While try to monetize as many
users as possible, [INAUDIBLE]

00:12:24.220 --> 00:12:29.920
even the user their choice of
currency such as IAP or ads.

00:12:29.920 --> 00:12:33.970
For conversion, understand what
uniquely motivates each segment

00:12:33.970 --> 00:12:38.290
of users will help you
create targeted offers.

00:12:38.290 --> 00:12:41.720
And for retention,
content is king

00:12:41.720 --> 00:12:45.170
and build a customizable
LiveOps system early, which

00:12:45.170 --> 00:12:46.670
will save you time later on.

